{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611601"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16227"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16227"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.62,0.12,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8918"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74623"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8918"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16227"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60117"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1777"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21228"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74623"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMammary duct ectasia is a benign condition of the breast that progresses through several pathological stages.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the final pathological stage of mammary duct ectasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Periductal inflammation and fibrosis","Duct obliteration with scarring","Duct dilation with stasis","Accumulation of proteinaceous secretions","Collection of foamy macrophages"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathological progression of mammary duct ectasia begins with \u003Cstrong\u003Educt dilation with stasis\u003C/strong\u003E of secretions, followed by inflammation. \u003Cstrong\u003EPeriductal inflammation and fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E then develops, along with \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccumulation of proteinaceous secretions\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EFoamy macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E appear as part of the inflammatory response. The final stage is characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Educt obliteration with scarring\u003C/strong\u003E as the chronic inflammatory process leads to complete fibrosis of the affected ducts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis condition typically affects women in their 40s and 50s and can present with nipple discharge, retraction, or a palpable mass that may be confused with breast cancer. The process is benign but can cause significant symptoms and anxiety for patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mammary duct ectasia is characterised by dilation and inflammation of breast ducts, progressing to fibrosis and eventual obliteration.","The condition typically affects perimenopausal women and can mimic breast cancer clinically."],"references":["Mohammed AA. Mammary duct ectasia in adult females; risk factors for the disease, a case control study. Ann Med Surg (Lond). 2021 Jan 18;62:140-144. doi: 10.1016/j.amsu.2021.01.023. PMID: 33520211; PMCID: PMC7820305.","Hamwi MW, Winters R. Mammary Duct Ectasia. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK557665/","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecolo